		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1185154">
                  
                  <div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				I hope removing EE is helping the developers to get the engine straight because I’m not sure the removal is of any benefit for the players.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div> There has been a nasty bug with EE for crafters since tools were given EE. In short, it counts the EE for tools <u>twice</u>. And I've lost several items due to it. The time I petitioned, I got back something different from what I had lost. <br />
<br />
Here's how the bug worked:<ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>Presume that 80% of your EE is currently used by clothing.</li><li>You equip a tool that uses 13% EE. Now you are at 93% EE.</li><li>You need to use that tool for a second application of some process - the computation shows that you have 7% EE left, and cannot equip the tool you currently have equipped so you <i>cannot</i> do that step. You get a yellow message &quot;missing tool type:&quot; (and the missing tool is blank). Since you are currently crafting, you cannot de-equip the tool and get back to 80% EE.</li><li>The only recourse is to press &quot;cancel&quot; and lose everything.</li></ol>I believe the addition of EE to crafting tools was in retaliation for the players pretty much only using level 45/50 tools that became available. On my server, we ask in /craft if anyone wants one, then mail it to them. Some of us saw it as a petty act that never should have been allowed out of some planning meeting, as anyone who played the game would have seen how it broke too much. <br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				And that is where I think it is going to become &quot;this is the price because I can&quot; line coming from the mouth of the crafters is all.<br />
<br />
1- yeah sell decons to them for probably 10-20 gold each. sell raw resources to them for 10-20 gold each ( rare and ultra rare that is ) 
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div> Crafters are currently wasting 50-100G deconstructing items to get the powders that other players want. I'm a tailor. The only focus anyone wants (on light armor) is hexes (healing and nuking focus). Weaponsmiths find that &quot;striking&quot; is the only wanted powder. One of my fellow tailors despairs that he can only sell hexing, and none of his other items sell, even at half the price of items with hexes on them. <br />
<br />
Instead of hexes, I'm getting buried in &quot;of might&quot; or &quot;accuracy&quot; powders. <br />
<br />
In general, I try to price things at 2x the most expensive component. Having spent 70G in the last week trying to get powders to make useful items, I'm not to thrilled about this change. Although it will let me purchase the powders I want, and let the rest rot in other player's banks.<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				Crafters will need to learn brand new recipes for all three continents. 
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div> It currently takes 2k faction to get caravel recipes, and 5k for galleon recipes (to get the recipes for that tier's housing recipes, one has to complete the quest for the ships first). If these recipes take more faction, they'll be non-starters. As it is, I've currently lost interest in obtaining the faction for caravels: just 300 more work orders to get it, and my tailor is at lvl 34 (the earliest one could do caravels would be level 31). With the market for sails/rigging for sloops trashed (one is lucky to recover the cost of parts to make the sails/rigging), there is no reason to make them.
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
